<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-10-09T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-10-09T12:00:00-05:00" n="154" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.2300/5: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harvey</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-10-09T17:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">October 9,
                                        1923—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 9—4:47
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>430. Your instruction number 879, July 18th.<note n="89" xml:id="d154fn89">Copy in Department file is unnumbered; see
                                footnote 85, <ref target="#pg_227">p. 227</ref>.</note> The
                            Admiralty will give Major Davidson, our air attaché here, all
                            information desired. The Air Ministry is expected to take the same
                            attitude.</p>
                        <p>Canada will assist the pathfinding officers in every way. There is no
                            objection to their Canadian itinerary as outlined in the above named
                            instruction.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Harvey</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>